<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
Dubya is telling the world (again) that we should all go in and get Saddam Hussein for a variety of evil things he's done and those U.N. resolutions he's breaking.  Dubya has so much respect for the U.N.<br>
<br>
Let's understand what resolution 1441 says about Iraq.  Saddam can't have chemical weapons.  Surprisingly, the inspectors can't find any chemical weapons, even with the help of the U.S. and U.K. governments who gave him the weapons in the 80s.  Saddam can't have biological weapons.  Again, even with the help of the supplying nations, the inspectors can't find any biological weapons.<br>
<br>
Saddam also can't have nuclear weapons.  The inspectors point out the correct pronunciation and still can't find any part of Iraq's nuclear weapons program.<br>
<br>
But Saddam is a murderous tyrant who could hand over his non-existent weapons to fundamentalist terrorists ... except that the fundamentalists are actually strong opponents of Saddam's entirely secular (that means non-religious) ruling party.<br>
<br>
But Saddam tortures his own people!  Yeah, okay, that part is likely true, but I don't see how firing three thousand cruise missiles in to a city of five million starving people is going to improve things.  Even if each missile only kills two civilians, the innocent death toll would exceed that of September 11, an atrocity we all agreed was evil, no matter what the goals or motivations of the people who made it happen.<br>
 <br>
Wishy-washy as the Canadian government is, we're doing the right thing sitting this one out.  As Dubya said last night, somewhat hypocritically, &quot;It is never an excuse to say 'I was just following orders.'&quot;<br>
